    comment: '<p>The HTML table is used to represent information in a table made of columns and rows.</p>\n<p>When creating a table in HTML the <code>&#x3C;table></code> element is used to create the entire table, the <code>&#x3C;tr></code>(Table Row) element is used to create the tables rows and the <code>&#x3C;td></code> (Table Data) element is used to create table data.</p>\n<p>Example of a simple table:</p>\n<pre><code class="language-html">&#x3C;table>\n  &#x3C;tr>\n    &#x3C;td>Matthew&#x3C;/td>\n    &#x3C;td>Denver&#x3C;/td>\n    &#x3C;td>Colorado&#x3C;/td>\n  &#x3C;/tr>\n  &#x3C;tr>\n    &#x3C;td>Liz&#x3C;/td>\n    &#x3C;td>San Francisco&#x3C;/td>\n    &#x3C;td>California&#x3C;/td>\n  &#x3C;/tr>\n&#x3C;/table>\n</code></pre>\n<p><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="320" height="78"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><rect width="320" height="78" fill="#FFF" rx="9"/><text fill="#000" font-family="TimesNewRomanPSMT, Times New Roman" font-size="16"><tspan x="21" y="33">Matthew</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="TimesNewRomanPSMT, Times New Roman" font-size="16"><tspan x="21" y="55">Liz</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="TimesNewRomanPSMT, Times New Roman" font-size="16"><tspan x="83" y="55">San Francisco</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="TimesNewRomanPSMT, Times New Roman" font-size="16"><tspan x="178" y="55">California</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="TimesNewRomanPSMT, Times New Roman" font-size="16"><tspan x="178" y="33">Colorado</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="TimesNewRomanPSMT, Times New Roman" font-size="16"><tspan x="83" y="33">Denver</tspan></text></g></svg></p>\n<!--[View CodePen](https://codepen.io/enkidevs/pen/JBXWLL)-->\n<p>Tables themselves in HTML without CSS can appear a little messy and confusing compared to those that are styled more appropriately.</p>\n<p><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="320" height="111"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><rect width="320" height="111" fill="#DCDDDF" rx="9"/><path fill="#FFF" d="M19 22h280v65H19z"/><text fill="#7E7F94" font-family="Roboto-Medium, Roboto" font-size="10" font-weight="400"><tspan x="30" y="41">Matthew</tspan></text><text fill="#7E7F94" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="30" y="74">Liz</tspan></text><text fill="#7E7F94" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="107" y="74">San Francisco</tspan></text><text fill="#7E7F94" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="207.5" y="74.5">California</tspan></text><text fill="#7E7F94" font-family="Roboto-Medium, Roboto" font-size="10" font-weight="400"><tspan x="207.5" y="41.5">Colorado</tspan></text><path stroke="#C8CAD7" stroke-linecap="square" d="M194 23v63.05"/><text fill="#7E7F94" font-family="Roboto-Medium, Roboto" font-size="10" font-weight="400"><tspan x="107" y="41">Denver</tspan></text><path stroke="#C8CAD7" stroke-linecap="square" d="M93.5 22.5v63.05m205 1.45h-279M299 54H20"/></g></svg></p>\n<!--[View CodePen](https://codepen.io/enkidevs/pen/JBXWbr)-->\n<p>Styling tables can take a little practice, as seen in the example above, and often use more specific selectors. Such as, in order to prevent the last column or bottom row from having styles that may look strange, properties on these rows (or cells) can be reset using the psudo class <code>:last-child</code> like this.</p>\n<pre><code class="language-css">tr:last-child {\n  border-bottom: none;\n}\n</code></pre>\n',
